439
47:26.700 --> 47:34.560
And as before we obtained the very best approximation to theta, with probability greater than 40%.

440
47:34.560 --> 47:41.730
That's pretty amazing. But if 40% is not good enough
as a measure of confidence,

441
47:41.730 --> 47:51.120
what we can do is to run the procedure a small number of times, and
take the mode of the outcomes, meaning the one that
appears most frequently.

442
47:51.120 --> 47:58.590
And if we do that, we'll be extremely likely to end up with a very good approximation to theta.

443
47:58.590 --> 48:05.430
Remember by the way that every time we run the
phase estimation procedure we have that the eigenvector
comes out unchanged.

444
48:05.430 --> 48:11.040
So it is available for us to run the procedure
multiple times like this.

445
48:11.040 --> 48:19.380
In short, we're gathering
statistics about theta, and the point is that by doing this we can get a very precise
approximation to theta

446
48:19.380 --> 48:25.680
with very high confidence, and we don't need that many iterations of the procedure to do this.

447
48:25.680 --> 48:29.250
And that is how the phase
estimation procedure works.

448
48:29.250 --> 48:36.570
In the last part of the lesson, we'll apply the technique
of phase estimation to the integer factorization problem.

449
48:36.570 --> 48:44.670
As I mentioned at the start of the video, the way this works is that we consider an intermediate problem known as the order finding problem.

450
48:44.670 --> 48:51.690
We'll see how we can solve
the order finding problem using phase estimation, and then we'll briefly discuss how solving the order finding problem

451
48:51.690 --> 48:55.020
allows us to factor integers efficiently.

452
48:55.020 --> 49:00.840
The second part is completely classical and I'll only summarize the
basic idea in this video.

453
49:00.840 --> 49:05.670
But let's begin with the
order finding problem.

454
49:05.670 --> 49:10.140
First, let's get some
handy notation in place.

455
49:10.140 --> 49:17.310
For every positive integer N, we define ZN to be the integers
zero through N minus one.

456
49:17.310 --> 49:24.330
So for instance, Z one has a
single element which is zero, Z two has elements zero and one,

457
49:24.330 --> 49:28.440
z three has elements zero,
one and two, and so on.

458
49:28.440 --> 49:31.680
So ZN is a set.

459
49:31.680 --> 49:39.240
But we can also think about
it as more than a set. We can think about arithmetic operations like addition and multiplication on ZN

460
49:39.240 --> 49:43.290
by defining them modular N.

461
49:43.290 --> 49:47.340
For example, let's suppose
N is equal to seven.

462
49:47.340 --> 49:53.400
We have that three and five
are elements of Z seven and if we multiply them together we get 15

463
49:53.400 --> 49:57.570
which leaves a remainder of
one after dividing by seven.

464
49:57.570 --> 50:04.590
Sometimes we express this by writing that three times five is
congruent to one module seven, like is written here.

465
50:04.590 --> 50:08.250
But we can also simply write that three times five equals one.

466
50:08.250 --> 50:12.750
Of course three times five
isn't normally equal to one, it's equal to 15.

467
50:12.750 --> 50:18.990
But when it's clear that
we're working in Z seven meaning that multiplication
is defined modular seven,

468
50:18.990 --> 50:23.640
we can simply write that
three times five equals one.

469
50:23.640 --> 50:30.690
Now among the elements
of ZN for any positive N, some of them will have
GCD equal to one with N

470
50:30.690 --> 50:36.510
and some won't. And the elements that do have GCD equal to one with N are special.

471
50:36.510 --> 50:42.780
and we write ZN star to refer to the set of just these elements.

472
50:42.780 --> 50:47.559
So for example, here's Z 21 star.

473
50:47.559 --> 50:56.730
among the elements of Z 21, which there are 21 of course, it turns out that 12 of them have GcD equals of one
with 21 and the rest don't.

474
50:56.730 --> 51:03.930
In particular anytime that
we have an element of Z 21 that's divisible by either
three or seven, we skip it.

475
51:03.930 --> 51:11.100
There are various reasons
why this set is special, and one of the reasons is that anytime we have an element of ZN star

476
51:11.100 --> 51:17.370
and we consider the positive
integer powers of that number, we will always eventually
hit the number one,

477
51:17.370 --> 51:22.680
where just like before we're talking about multiplication modular N.

478
51:22.680 --> 51:28.500
the smallest positive integer power that gives us one is called
the order of that element.

479
51:28.500 --> 51:34.170
For example, think about the element A equals four in Z 21 star.

480
51:34.170 --> 51:41.070
four times four is 16, which is not equal to one modular of 21, but if we multiply by four one more time,

481
51:41.070 --> 51:46.320
we get 64, and 64 modular
21 is equal to one.

482
51:46.320 --> 51:51.300
So the order of four modular 21 is three.

483
51:51.300 --> 51:55.890
Getting to one like this always happens for all of the elements of ZN star.

484
51:55.890 --> 52:00.180
And by the way, it never
happens for elements of ZN that aren't in ZN star.

485
52:00.180 --> 52:06.930
So having GCD equal to
one with N like this is both necessary and
sufficient for this to happen.

486
52:06.930 --> 52:15.630
And just to finish up the
example of N equals 21, here are the smallest
positive integer powers for which this works for
each element of Z 21 star,

487
52:15.630 --> 52:21.835
and they can each be checked one by one.

488
52:21.835 --> 52:30.450
And now we can state the
order finding problem, which is simply to find the order for a given element in ZN star.

